Anyway, if the Battle of Bunker Hill was a British victory yet nobody claims it is, then why is Borodino the only exception? Borodino was a French victory, but they got absolutely wrecked by the conflict and the battle was a crucial turning point in the downfall of Napoleon and his empire.

So to conclude, declaring the Battle of Borodino to be a French victory is very odd, as the efforts committed by the Imperial Russian Army against the Grande Arm茅e absolutely devastated France's ability to wage any more wars and conquests, and later on, the ability to defend itself as a nation from the superior forces of the Russian Empire, the Kingdom of Prussia, the British and Austrian Empires, etc. Anyway, I hope you have an amazing day! Thanks for reading.

Finally, the Russian Empire, knowing that they had devastated Napoleon and his Grande Arm茅e, managed to fool and trick the military genius by purposely luring him into Moscow and then trapping him within it, inflicting even more catastrophic losses against him and his men as he tried to escape, which eventually lead to his demise and the overall collapse of his empire entirely.

With that being said, however, it is generally accepted by most academic professionals that the Imperial French and Imperial Russian armies both suffered tremendous losses; No army suffered less or more casualties and the two empires were equally bludgeoned and weakened by each other from this conflict. However, the Russian Empire had an advantage over Napoleonic France as it was able to replenish its losses quickly whilst France could not.

This is a misconception. Whilst there are various individual historians who give their own viewpoint on the casualties suffered during the Battle of Borodino, none of these estimations are verifiable and are based solely on speculation.
